{"questionId":"9069736","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider the following reaction:</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">Cu<sup>2+</sup> (aq) + Fe (s) → Fe<sup>2+ </sup>(aq) + Cu (s)</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>The mass spectrum for copper is shown:</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/7c295d32bea0c3b0f862cc7701d01265f4636e78.png\"></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><sup>Source:&nbsp;WebElements, n.d. <em>Copper: isotope data</em> [online] Available at:</sup><br><sup> https://www.webelements.com/copper/isotopes.html&nbsp;[Accessed 6 October 2021].</sup></p>\n<p><br>Show how a relative atomic mass of copper of 63.62 can be obtained from this&nbsp;mass spectrum.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mfenced><mrow><mn>63</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>69</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>65</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mn>100</mn></mfrac></math></p>\n<p><em><strong>OR</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>65</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>63</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>63</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>62</mn></math>&nbsp; <em><strong>AND&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></em><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>31</mn><mo> </mo><mo>/</mo><mo> </mo><mn>31</mn></math>«%»&nbsp; <em><strong>AND&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></em><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>69</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>/</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>69</mn></math>«%» ✔</p>","meta":{"questionId":"9069736","referenceCode":"22N.2.hl.TZ0.3b","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"The mass spectrum for copper is shown: Source: WebElements, n.d. Copper: isotope data [online] Available at: https://www.webelements.com/copper/isotopes.html